body:
The usage of const-generic types with specialization started to cause errors since nightly-2020-05-20 (rustc 2020-05-19).

All the following samples build successfully and work with nightly-2020-05-19 toolchain (rustc 2020-05-18) and earlier.

### Code

[Complete on playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=bd7c3a432e0949d89eefd24862b1d2aa)

```rust
#![feature(const_generics)]
#![feature(specialization)]

trait ValTypeSelect {
    type ValTypeInner;
}

struct UseSmallInt<const N: bool>{}

impl<const N: bool> ValTypeSelect for UseSmallInt<N> {
    default type ValTypeInner = i32;
}
impl ValTypeSelect for UseSmallInt<true> { 
    type ValTypeInner = i8; 
}


struct MyStruct<const VAL: usize>
{
    val: <UseSmallInt<{VAL!=0}> as ValTypeSelect>::ValTypeInner,
}
```

Gives the error:

```
error[E0284]: type annotations needed: cannot satisfy `<UseSmallInt<{VAL!=0}> as ValTypeSelect>::ValTypeInner == _`
  --> src/main.rs:18:5
   |
18 |     val: <UseSmallInt<{VAL!=0}> as ValTypeSelect>::ValTypeInner,
   |     ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^ cannot satisfy `<UseSmallInt<{VAL!=0}> as ValTypeSelect>::ValTypeInner == _`
```

To raise an error the const parameter (`VAL`) may be used in const expression in any way except "path statement" like `UseSmallInt<{VAL; true}>`. So this fails to compile too ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=89cb4af0afa111d3e9b673a219d92619)):

```rust
struct MyStruct<const VAL: usize>
{
    val: <UseSmallInt<{VAL+VAL; true}> as ValTypeSelect>::ValTypeInner,
}
```

### ICE case

The ICE is encountered in a special case ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=6bc44e86e27c8f024b30eafaabceffac)):

```rust
#[derive(Clone)]
struct IntermediateStruct<const N: bool> {
    field1: <UseSmallInt<N> as ValTypeSelect>::ValTypeInner,
    field2: (),
}

struct MyStruct<const VAL: usize> {
    intermed: IntermediateStruct<{VAL+VAL; true}>,
}

impl<const VAL: usize> MyStruct<VAL> {
    fn consume_val(&self) {
        let _x = self.intermed.clone();
    }
}
```

Error:

```
error: internal compiler error: dtorck encountered internal error
  --> src/lib.rs:27:13
   |
27 |         let _x = self.intermed.clone();
   |             ^^

error: internal compiler error: dtorck encountered internal error
  --> src/lib.rs:27:18
   |
27 |         let _x = self.intermed.clone();
   |                  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

```

The ICE raises when the last field in `IntermediateStruct` is not a const-generic-with-specialization member. If the field order is opposite, the general "type annotations needed" is reported ([playground](https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=nightly&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=4557b12ad6ad415919f431c0bf7c0374)):

```rust
#[derive(Clone)]
struct IntermediateStruct<const N: bool> {
    field2: (),
    field1: <UseSmallInt<N> as ValTypeSelect>::ValTypeInner,
}
```

